// v8.5: SCORING FIXES - Add employee-user persona for B2B2C patterns
const items = $input.all();

const systemPrompt = `You are classifying companies by their PRIMARY customer persona.

Classify as ONE of:
- "business-user": B2B SaaS where end users are non-technical business professionals (sales, marketing, HR, finance, operations, legal, executives). The COMPANY buys and the COMPANY's employees use.
- "employee-user": B2B2C model where the COMPANY buys but CONSUMERS/PATIENTS use (healthcare apps for patients, employee wellness, benefits platforms, telehealth patient portals). Key signal: end user is a consumer/patient, not an employee doing their job.
- "developer": End users are primarily developers, engineers, DevOps, SRE, data engineers, or highly technical practitioners
- "mixed": Multiple personas are equally important primary users

Signals for EMPLOYEE-USER (B2B2C) - these should NOT be classified as business-user:
- Patient-facing apps (Oshi Health, Koa Health patterns)
- Mental health/wellness platforms where employees/patients use the app
- Healthcare apps sold to employers/providers but used by patients
- Benefits platforms where employees are the end users
- "Member experience", "patient engagement", "employee wellness"

Signals for DEVELOPER-AS-CUSTOMER:
- API-first products
- Developer tools, SDKs, CLI tools
- Infrastructure, observability, monitoring
- Data engineering, ETL, data pipelines
- DevOps, CI/CD, deployment
- Code review, testing, debugging tools
- Database tools, query engines
- "Built for engineers" or "by developers, for developers"

Signals for BUSINESS-USER-CUSTOMER:
- "No code required", "Self-serve", "Non-technical users"
- Sales enablement, CRM, marketing tools
- HR admin tools (not employee-facing wellness)
- Healthcare PROVIDER workflows (clinicians using software)
- Business intelligence for business users
- Customer support, success platforms

Respond with ONLY one word: business-user, employee-user, developer, or mixed`;

return items.map(item => {
